Volume 193, February 2018, Pages 530-537

Sample handling and data processing for fluorescent excitation-emission matrix (EEM) of dissolved organic matter (DOM)

Author links open overlay panel,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.chemosphere.2017.11.069Get rights and content

Highlights

  • â€¢

    Commonly applied biocides can negatively impact the fluorescence EEM surrogate.

  • â€¢

    Sodium bisulfite was determined to be the most appropriate oxidant quenching agent for EEM.

  • â€¢

    Recycled water samples were stable in terms of EEM when stored at 4 Â°C for 21-days.

  • â€¢

Abstract

In environmental engineering and science, fluorescent excitation-emission matrix (EEM) has increasingly been utilized to characterize chromophoric dissolved organic matter (CDOM). This study aims to delineate EEM data processing, including calculation of total fluorescence (TF) which is an emerging water quality parameter often used as a surrogate for micropollutant removal by advanced water treatment processes. In addition, sample handling procedures such as storage, use of preservatives, and oxidant quenching agents were evaluated. In this study, three antimicrobial preservatives were tested: sodium azide, sodium omadine, and thymol. All the tested preservatives altered optical properties of samples, and were therefore not suitable for the preservation of EEM samples. Without preservative, storage of samples at 4 Â°C maintained TF within 7.5% of its original value for 21 days, while TF of samples stored at the room temperature more drastically changed (up to 15%). The impacts of three oxidant quenching agents including ascorbic acid, sodium bisulfite, and sodium thiosulfate on EEM were also tested. Among the quenching agents, sodium bisulfite was found to be suitable since it little influenced optical properties of samples while the other two were not favorable due to interference. We also scrutinized the use of TF as surrogate to monitor micropollutant rejection by nanofiltration membrane.

1. Introduction

Fluorescence spectroscopy is an analytical technique that has been widely implemented to characterize fluorophores of organic matter in the natural water (Coble, 1996). Since fluorescence spectroscopy provides three-dimensional matrix (i.e., excitation, emission, and fluorescence intensity), it is very useful to characterize natural organic matter (NOM) derived from different origins. For instance, the fluorescence intensity indicates the amount of fluorophores in the water while the fluorescence peak maxima located at different pairs of excitation and emission wavelengths provide qualitative information that can differentiate the origins of NOM (e.g., humic acid, fluvic acid, soluble microbial products, aromatic protein, etc.) (Zhang et al., 2009).

Recently, fluorescence spectroscopy has been actively studied as a surrogate of micropollutant occurrence and/or their removal efficacy by various physico-chemical water treatment processes. Sgroi et al. demonstrated the application of excitation-emission matrix (EEM) as a surrogate for monitoring micropollutants in wastewater-impacted rivers (Sgroi et al., 2017b). Another application can be monitoring of micropollutant removal by conventional wastewater treatment plants consisting of primary and secondary treatments (Sgroi et al., 2017a). The primary benefit of fluorescence as a surrogate is fast and sensitive in measurement, and minimal in sample preparation. These benefits can be maximized when applying fluorescence technique to monitoring the efficacy of treatment with low retention time. Direct potable water reuse (DPR) can be an example. DPR is a reuse scheme which has â€œpipe-to-pipeâ€ connection between the reclaimed water treatment facility and the water distribution system (Bouwer, 2000). Since primary water source for potable water reuse is wastewater effluent that is a receiving water body of anthropogenic micropollutants such as pharmaceuticals, personal care products, industrial compounds, and synthetic hormones, the verification of infallible treatment is of paramount importance to ensure the treated water quality. However, monitoring treatment efficacy for micropollutant abatement in a real-time manner remains challenging (Park et al., 2015). Current analytical techniques for micropollutant identification heavily depend on mass spectrometry, which often requires highly sensitive equipment, extensive sample preparation, and highly skilled operators. Therefore, fluorescence spectroscopy can be a viable option as a real-time monitoring tool for the micropollutant abatement.

Recently, total fluorescence (TF)â€”the summation of regionally integrated fluorescence intensitiesâ€”has been increasingly applied as a surrogate and its reduction exhibited correlations with micropollutant abatement in various physico-chemical treatment processes including ozone oxidation (Gerrity et al., 2012, Park et al., 2017a), activated carbon adsorption (Anumol et al., 2015, Ziska et al., 2016), and ultraviolet (UV)-AOP (Yu et al., 2015) for water reuse. Even though use of TF as surrogate is emerging and increasingly draws attention, little research paper holistically delineated data process of fluorescence measurement and calculation of TF. Furthermore, while sample preservation and storage strategy have been studied for micropollutants (Vanderford et al., 2011), no study suggesting a method for such sample handling has been demonstrated. Therefore, this study aims to delineate fluorescence data process and TF calculation. In addition, three biocides as preservative for fluorescence sample storage and three oxidant quenching agents were tested to suggest sample handling strategy. Furthermore, it was attempted to demonstrate use of TF as surrogate to predict micropollutant rejection by nanofiltration (NF) membrane.

2. Material and methods

2.1. EEM data processing

The overall flow diagram of data processing for EEM is illustrated in Fig. 1. The first step of EEM data processing is to eliminate light scattering peaks such as Rayleigh and Raman peaks. The light scattering peaks inherently occur in aqueous samples. For instance, Rayleigh scattering occurs due interaction between the excitation light and water molecules. In addition, the presence of DOM can also induce Tyndall scattering that accentuates the extent of scattered light by Rayleigh effect (Ewald et al., 1983). In order to eliminate light scattering, we employed a three-dimensional Delaunay interpolation method (Zepp et al., 2004). Specifically, the wavelength-specific Rayleigh and Raman scatter peaks were excised and the missing regions were filled by interpolation using the surrounding data points. This light scattering elimination procedure was conducted using MATLAB R2017a (The Mathworks, Inc.) and its numerical code is available in a previously published manuscript (Zepp et al., 2004).

Once light scattering peaks are removed, the next step is to correct inner filter effects. The spectral intensity is not proportional to the concentration of fluorophores due to self-quenching where incident light is absorbed as passing through light-absorbing media, thus losing energy before reaching the point where luminescence occurs (called the primary inner filter effect). Furthermore, the emitted light can be re-absorbed before leaving the media (called secondary inner filter effect). In order to correct these effects, the following mathematical formulation was utilized (Lakowicz, 2013).(1)Fcorr=Fobs10(Absex+Absem2)where Fcorr and Fobs refer to the corrected and observed fluorescence intensities, respectively; and Absex and Absem indicate the absorbance at excitation wavelength and emission wavelength, respectively. This equation was formulated based on the theory that absorbance attenuates the excitation and emission by antilog of âˆ’0.5Absex and âˆ’0.5Absem, respectively. There is another option to eliminate the inner filter effect: dilution of samples to which absorbance at or below 0.05 (89.1% transmittance) across the scanned wavelength range (Kubista et al., 1994). It should be borne in mind that dilution can increase the effects of instrumental noise on fluorescence intensity.

The inner effect-corrected fluorescence intensity from a fluorescence spectrometer is in arbitrary units (AUs), which challenges quantitative inter-comparison across different instruments. In addition, even using the same instrument, lamp performance will deteriorate as the lamp life time decreases, thus causing different fluorescence intensities. Therefore, the conversion of AU to an inter-comparable unit is necessary. To this end, two normalization methods are often employed: one using Raman peak of pure water and the other using quinine sulfate as a fluorescence quantum yield standard. In this study, the normalization technique using Raman peak of MilliQ water (hereinafter, Raman normalization) was utilized (Lawaetz and Stedmon, 2009). After Raman normalization, one can obtain fluorescence intensity in Raman units (RU), which can be universally compared. Raman normalization can be done by dividing Fcorr by the area of Raman peak area. Its mathematical formulation is shown as follows.(2)Ffinal(R.U.)=Fcorrâˆ«Î»em,lowerÎ»em,upperFDI(Î»em)=Fcorrâˆ«427.9nm370.8nmFDI,ex350nm(Î»em)where Ffinal is the final fluorescence intensity in RU; FDI is the fluorescence intensity of DI water; FDI,ex350nm is the fluorescence intensity of deionized (DI) water at 350 nm excitation wavelength; and Î»em,lower and Î»em,upper are the lower and upper boundaries of wavelengths for the Raman peak, respectively. Here, 350 nm excitation wavelength was chosen for the Raman peak integration since it is widely adopted (Stedmon et al., 2003, Murphy et al., 2010). Raman peak position and band span depend on the excitation wavelength. For instance, if the excitation wavelength is 350 nm, Raman peak appears at 397.3 nm and theoretical boundaries of the Raman peak are 370.8 nm and 427.9 nm, respectively. It is noteworthy that RU can be converted to quinine sulfate (QS) equivalent by dividing the RU value by 0.0767 (Lawaetz and Stedmon, 2009).

A regional integration method originally proposed by Chen et al. has been widely used to quantitatively assess DOM fractions (Chen et al., 2003). This technique was further applied to calculate total fluorescence (TF), which has been applied for measuring organic chemical treatment efficacy in potable water reuse (Anumol et al., 2015). Total fluorescence is the summation of regionally integrated fluorescence intensity (Park et al., 2017a). In order to calculate TF, fluorescence excitation/emission boundaries for integration are defined. In the current work, the boundaries (Table 1) proposed in previously literature were adopted (Chen et al., 2003). In case the instrument scanning range of wavelength does not cover the boundaries suggested, a more limited set of wavelengths may be applied. For instance, this study employed data scanned from the excitation wavelength of 225 nm. In this case, 200 nm of the excitation wavelength boundary for Region I, II, and III can be modified to 225 nm.

2.2. Sample collection and measurement of EEM

Secondary wastewater effluent was collected at two different wastewater treatment facilities located in Tucson, Arizona, USA. The wastewater effluent collected at the first wastewater treatment plant (WWTP) is named as WWTP1 and one for the second WWTP is labelled with WWTP2. Their bulk water qualities including dissolved organic carbon (DOC), UV absorbance at 254 nm (UVA254), specific UV absorbance (SUVA), and alkalinity were summarized in Table S1 in the supplementary material.

The collected water was stored in an 1 L amber glass bottle at 4 Â°C until measurement. Samples were filtered using 0.45 Î¼m PVDF syringe filter (EMD Millipore) to remove particulates which can result in light scattering. The filtered samples were allowed to warm up to room temperature prior to measurement. UV and fluorescence spectra were simultaneously measured using a Horiba Aqualog fluorometer. UV spectra were scanned from 200 nm to 580 nm wavelength and the obtained UV spectra were used to correct inner filter effects. Fluorescence was scanned with excitation wavelengths from 225 to 450 nm in 5 nm increments and emission wavelengths from 250 to 580 nm in 1 nm increments. A quartz cuvette (10 Ã— 10 mm) was filled with filtered samples for measurement and then rinsed with MilliQ water between samples.

2.3. Preservative and oxidant quenching agents

Three preservatives were selected: sodium azide (laboratory grade, Fisher Scientific), sodium omadine (2-Mercaptopyridine-N-oxide, sodium salt monohydrate, 98%, ACROS Organicsâ„¢), and thymol (99%, ACROS Organicsâ„¢). In order to evaluate the effects of oxidant quenching agents, l-Ascorbic acid (sodium salt, 99%, ACROS Organicsâ„¢), sodium bisulfite (99%, Sigma-Aldrich), and sodium thiosulfate (Reagent ACS, ACROS Organicsâ„¢) were tested. Chemical structure and molecular weight (MW) of the preservatives and oxidant quenching agents are shown in Table S2. Two concentrations for the preservatives were applied: 30 mg/L and 60 mg/L. These concentrations are in the range of practically applied concentrations (Gillett and Ayers, 1991, Xue et al., 2009). Similarly, 25 mg/L and 50 mg/L of the quenching agents were selected based on the practical oxidant concentration applied in water treatments (see Section 3.3).

2.4. Membrane filtration

Closed-loop membrane filtration was conducted to demonstrate use of TF surrogate to predict rejection of micropollutants in surface water by NF membrane (Park et al., 2017b). Colorado river water was used as feed water and 50 ng/L of 17 micropollutants were spiked into the feed water (Water Quality 1) and six compounds whose concentrations in permeate were above method detection limit were reported in this study. Structure and physical properties of the six micropollutants are shown in Table S3. A spiral wound membrane system with two pressure vessels was operated in parallel. Two Dow Filmtecâ„¢ NF270-4040 membrane elements were employed with a one-micron pre-filter. Constant pressure and feed flow rate was employed during filtration (350 kPa and 20 L/min, respectively). Concentrate stream was sent back into the feed tank while permeate stream was discarded. Samples were collected at the desired recovery rate: 10, 20, 30, 40, 50 and 85%. For surrogate model validation, Colorado river water collected at a different time (Water Quality 2) was used with the same spiking concentration of micropollutants and samples were collected at 40% recovery rate.

2.5. Micropollutant analysis

Seventeen micropollutants were measured using an online solid-phase extraction module coupled to an ultra-HPLC tandem mass spectrometer (UHPLC-MS/MS) from Agilent Technologies (Palo Alto, CA). A FlexCube module was hyphenated with an Agilent 1290 Infinity UHPLC to implement automated online solid phase extraction using a polymeric solid phase extraction cartridge. Details of the analytical method can be found in a previous publication (Anumol and Snyder, 2015). Among the 17 micropollutants, six compounds (Table S3) showing noticeable correlation with TF reduction were selected for the surrogate correlation study (Section 3.4).

3. Results and discussion

3.1. Analysis of a wastewater effluent

Fig. 2 illustrates the EEM data process for a wastewater effluent. Rayleigh and Raman scattering peaks plagued fluorescence peaks. Particularly, the second-order Raman scattering interfered with the soluble microbial product-like area and the second-order Rayleigh scattering hampered the reading of fulvic acid-like region. After the elimination of such scattering peaks, inner filter effect correction amended the reduced fluorescence intensity by the self-quenching effect, which yielded greater fluorescence intensity particularly at low excitation and emission wavelengths. The Raman normalization converted AU to RU, allowing comparisons across different instruments. The TF value and derived parameters during TF calculation are shown in Table S4.

3.2. The effects of preservatives on EEM

In order to investigate the impacts of preservatives on EEM, three biocides were selected: sodium azide, sodium omadine, and thymol. Fig. 3 illustrates the effects of the three selected preservatives on EEM and UV absorbance. An ideal preservative, or any other additive such as an oxidant quenching agent, is a chemical that does not absorb light. As shown in Fig. 3, the selected compounds absorbed light at different wavelengths. Sodium azide absorbs light at the wavelength less than 260 nm, therefore influencing fluorescence intensity at which the excitation wavelength is less than 260 nm. When sodium azide is dissolved in water, it is dissociated into sodium and azide ions. Azide ion (N3âˆ’) is a linear triatomic molecule and exhibits similar absorbance characteristics with other linear triatomic molecules with the same number of valence (i.e., sixteen) such as CO2 and CS2 (Closson and Gray, 1963). As a result, two spectral bands can be expected: one at 230 nm and 188 nm. Absorbance band at 230 nm was partially masked by the stronger absorbance at 188 nm whose maxima was not shown due to the limit of scanning range (Closson and Gray, 1963). A study claimed that use of 26 mg/L sodium azide does not affect fluorescence intensity (Patel-Sorrentino et al., 2002), which contradicts with our findings. Since azide ion absorbs light at less than 260 nm, the addition of 30 mg/L sodium azide (similar concentration with the Patel-Sorrentino et al.â€™s study) should mask the fluorescence at the same excitation wavelength range such as regions for aromatic protein and fluvic acid-like matter. Omadine is an aromatic heterocyclic nitrogenous compound and exists mainly as anionic tautomeric forms (thiolâ€”thione) at neutral pH (Reszka and Chignell, 1995). Three absorbance peaks at 246, 282, and 334 nm were observed in the given concentrations and substantially reduced fluorescence intensity over the scanned wavelengths (Reszka and Chignell, 1995). EEM of thymol-containing samples were different from the other preservatives as thymol fluoresces while the other two preservatives only absorb light and do not fluoresce. Thymol is an alkylphenolic compound and possesses similar spectroscopic property with phenol, which shows the maximum absorbance at 275 nm (Linstrom and Mallard, 2017). Phenol is also a fluorophore and addition of electron-donating groups such as methyl and ethyl does not change fluorescence intensity drastically compared to phenol (De Ruiter et al., 1988). Therefore, thymol can interfere fluorescence measurement.

Since the three selected biocides altered optical properties of a wastewater effluent, none of them should be used for EEM sample preservation. Therefore, it is valuable to test sample preservation time in typical sample storage environments. In general, the best storage practice for aqueous samples is to store them in a 4 Â°C refrigerator. Hence, we kept two identical wastewater effluents in separate amber bottles (i.e., duplicates) in a 4 Â°C refrigerator and at room temperature (23 Â± 1 Â°C) for 21 days. Fig. 4 depicts the comparison of TF value changes with respect to time between 4 Â°C and room temperature of sample storage. For the first nine days, TF gradually increases for the both temperatures, but to different extents. After nine days, TF decreased and subsequently maintained its value by the end of storage experiment. The samples stored at the room temperature exhibited greater TF increase and the change exceeded 10% of the original value after just five days of storage while the 4 Â°C storage temperature only changed by 7.5% over the entire testing period of 21 days. Even with the first day of storage at the room temperature TF increase by over 5% compared to its original value. These data demonstrate that it is critical to store samples at a low temperature (e.g., 4 Â°C) as soon as possible in order to maintain the optical properties of aqueous samples. Because the lower temperature caused lower extent of TF change, it can be presumed that TF change was attributed to microbial activity. While the mechanism of TF change is not a scope of this study and needs to be further studied, release of aromatic and/or hydrophobic organic matter from microbes can be presumed (Saadi et al., 2006).

3.3. The impacts of quenching agents on EEM

In water treatment, oxidation processes are widely applied for disinfection and for attenuation of many classes of organic compounds (such as pharmaceuticals, personal care products, pesticide, industrial compounds, and steroid hormones) (Park et al., 2017a). In order to study the kinetics of chemical degradation by oxidation processes, the reaction should be stopped at a specific reaction time by quenching residual oxidants. In addition, quenching is important to study the formation kinetics of disinfection by-product (DBP) (Roccaro et al., 2009). Moreover, wastewater effluents are generally chlorinated and have free chlorine or combined chlorine such as monochloramine, which can degrade analytes over the period of sample shipping and storage. In the current study, ascorbic acid, sodium bisulfite, and sodium thiosulfate were selected as oxidant quenching agents. As shown in Fig. 5, ascorbic acid exhibited absorbance at 240â€“300 nm, hence reducing fluorescence intensity wavelengths substantially. Ascorbic acid has a conjugated enone (carbonyl + olefin) and absorbs UV light at 265 nm as maximum, which yielded the fluorescence intensity reduction of a wastewater sample at such excitation wavelength. Sodium bisulfite and sodium thiosulfate are inorganic salts. While sodium thiosulfate reduces fluorescence intensity at wavelengths less than 260 nm, sodium bisulfite showed little change of UV absorbance and fluorescence spectra, which is in agreement with a previous report (Guenther et al., 2001). Therefore, it can be concluded that sodium bisulfite is a suitable quenching agent for EEM samples. It is noteworthy that 25 mg/L sodium bisulfite can quench 17.0 mg/L chlorine (Cl2) and 11.5 mg/L ozone (O3) (see the following stoichiometries), respectively. It is noteworthy that the concentrations of the tested oxidant quenching agents correspond to the orders of magnitude of oxidant quenching agents that are typically applied in wastewater treatment plants. For instance, the typical range of chlorine dosages are between 5 mg/L and 20 mg/L (USEPA, 1999). In addition, the applied ozone dose ranges 0.5 mg O3/mg C and 1.0 mg O3/mg C. Since the general DOC of secondary wastewater effluents is in the range of 3 mg/L and 20 mg/L, the oxidant quenching agent concentrations are in practical range too. It is noteworthy that residual oxidant concentrations to be quenched would be lower than the applied oxidant doses, so one should measure or properly estimate the residual oxidant concentration when calculating the quenching agent dosage.(6)NaHSO3+HOClâ†’NaHSO4+HCl(7)NaHSO3+O3â†’NaHSO4+O2

3.4. Surrogate correlation of micropollutant abatement with TF reduction in NF membrane process

In the preceding sections, TF calculation procedure was elucidated. In this section, surrogate correlation between TF reduction and micropollutant attenuation is presented. NF270 is a loose NF membrane and its molecular weight cut-off (MWCO) was reported to be âˆ¼400 Da (Rohani et al., 2011). PFOA showed the greatest removal at the corresponding recovery rate among the tested compounds. PFOA is greater in MW than MWCO of the membrane and was effectively rejected by the membrane via size exclusion mechanism. The other four micropollutants are smaller than MWCO of the membrane and showed removal ranging from 78% to 99%. It was observed that the rejection of the other micropollutants was proportional to their MW except for atenolol. Atenolol (MW 266 Da) has lower removal than smaller micropollutants including atrazine (MW 216 Da) and naproxen (230 Da). This is likely due to the hydrophilic nature of atenolol at a neutral pH, which cause less adsorptive interaction with membrane surface during its transport (see Log Dow at pH 7 in Table S3) (Yoon et al., 2007). Interestingly, micropollutant was attenuated to the greater extent as recovery rate increased (Fig. S1). Particularly, âˆ¼5% rejection increase was found for atrazine, atenolol, naproxen and simazine as recovery increased from 10% to 85%. The micropollutants with higher rejection (i.e., PFOA and trimethoprim) showed smaller extent of increase in rejection. The increased recovery rate in a closed-loop filtration caused the augmented ionic strength and organic content in the feed water. Higher NOM concentration can improve micropollutant rejection, while ionic strength can negatively influence micropollutant rejection (de la Rubia et al., 2008). Therefore, the increased NOM content predominantly influenced the rejection characteristics of the tested micropollutants. Another physical phenomenon influencing micropollutant rejection was charge interaction between compounds and membrane surface, but no noticeable trend was found for the tested compounds.

The rationale for fluorescence surrogate use is that water treatment process (NF membrane in this study) removes fluorophores along with micropollutants. For instance, the increased recovery escalated both TF reduction and micropollutant attenuation (Fig. S1). General methods for correlation is to plot either percent or log attenuation of micropollutants versus that of TF (Gerrity et al., 2012, Ziska et al., 2016, Park et al., 2017a). When plotting micropollutant rejection versus reduction in TF in percent, linear correlations were found (Fig. 6). This linear trend can be utilized as a characteristic equation to predict micropollutant rejection by the same NF membrane. It is noteworthy that the trend lines were obtained using a surface water (Water Quality 1 in Fig. 6) and another surface water collected at the same location, but different time (Water Quality 2 in Fig. 6) was used for validation. The data used for validation (Water Quality 2) were well aligned with the data for Water Quality 1 and showed low values of prediction errors (<4%), indicating that the surrogate model can be used to predict micropollutant rejection in seasonally variable water quality. While this study showed good prediction, only two water qualities were tested and they are similar in terms of DOC and total dissolved solid (TDS) concentrations (3.5 mg/L DOC and 605 mg/L TDS for Water Quality 1 and 4.2 mg/L DOC and 628 mg/L DOC for Water quality 2). Therefore, a systematic experimental design to delineate the use of TF surrogate models for different water qualities such as wastewater effluents is suggested as future study.

4. Conclusions

This study describes the procedures and calculations using for EEM data processing, including TF calculation. In addition, sample handling such as storage and the use of preservative and oxidant quenching agents was evaluated. None of the tested biocide preservatives were suitable for EEM analyses since they altered optical properties of samples. Without preservatives, TF change over time can be minimized by storing samples at 4 Â°C. Less than 7.5% TF change was observed over 21 days of storage at 4 Â°C whereas storage at the room temperature yielded greater TF change. Oxidant quenching agents were also evaluated to determine potential impact on EEM results. It was found that sodium bisulfite did not alter UV absorbance spectra and EEM at 25 and 50 mg/L and is suitable as an oxidant quenching agent. However ascorbic acid and sodium thiosulfate absorbed UV light, therefore not suitable as quenching agents.

Use of surrogate correlation between TF reduction and micropollutant rejection by a closed-loop NF membrane system was also investigated. Since TF reduction and micropollutant rejection exhibited similar ascending trend as recovery increased, linear correlation between TF reduction and micropollutant was found. This trend line could be applied to predict micropollutant removal in a water collected at a different season. While TF was shown as a good surrogate for micropollutant rejection in a NF membrane, limited number of water qualities was tested in this study. Hence, broad spectrum of water qualities is suggested to be tested as a future study.
